here's my pitch in the Peggy conversation.

>You're a therapist, specialising in helping returning veterans adjust to a civilian life.
>Your newest patient is Peggy Patterson, long time veteran of over 20 years as Military Police.
>You do home appointments, visiting her house you find it quite orderly, unnaturally so.
>Most of the shelves are empty, she doesn't keep much around. In fact the place doesn't seem very lived in with minimal furniture or personal things.
>When you sit her down she's reluctant to talk, holding a permanent scowl with deep and dark eyes.
>You try to get her to open up, you ask her about her experiences and try to lend an ear. She only answers in short sentences, questioning if you're just a waste of time and money.
>she says she's doing fine at civilian life, she works as private security and she doesn't need any help.
>Your job is to read people, she's not good at lying.
>She gives it away subtly.
> She's wearing the same set of pressed clothing everyday of the week.
>Her fridge is barely stocked and she appears to struggle to make basic meals.
>She has two voices, one harsh and regimental, the other still gruff but much more gentle. She slips in and out of them depending on the situation, she never realises it.
>She has nothing in her life beyond her job, like she left most of herself behind when she was discharged.
>She's alone too, no partner and most of her family dead, far away or too old to help her.
>She's not exactly healthy either.
>The piles of fag butts on the window sill, the spirits atop the fridge, the junk food wrappers. She brushes it off when you bring it up to her and you haven't told her about the box of heavy painkillers you found.
>Ones that could easily OD her on a large enough dose.
>She's alive, but she's not living and you know if you don't step it will get worse.
>You have a long road ahead of you with helping this woman.
>And you begin drawing up a plan in order to do so.

What next?

Anonymous Mon 03 Aug 2020 09:17:07 No.31889822 Report
Quoted By:
>>31888747
Girl needs a hobby, and some friends. If I was approaching things as an actual professional I'd try and get her into group therapy. I wouldn't *call* it group therapy of course. They never do that. "Hey Anon, you might enjoy this meet up some of the other vets have every week or so. We meet at <location> it's a good time, you should come." Same deal with getting her locked in with the various vet social groups. That should help a lot all on it's own. Once she's taken a suggestion from me and it's panned out... that's leverage to get into her mind and world a bit, because you've shown you're on side. You're not just another shrink, you get it.

Now if I'm approaching it from a "Score a retired MWD" angle... not sure honestly. I'd either start with talking her into an excursion somewhere. Anywhere. That might be a chance for fun. Even if that means getting a beer with her. OR start with making her dinner. Either at hers or have her over. Justify it as a new modern therapy protocol that involves great steaks and decent beer. Food is the way to the heart in many respects, and a change in environment, especially from a sterile environment is critical for working with someone's mind. A change in that environment, say a friendly guy making you dinner in your kinda desolate home... can also affect those changes.

Lets say all races are equally smart yes?
Heat is a common trait among anthros, something that wouldn't burden mankind. We breed whenever we please, meaning that whomever came out on top in any engagement would still fall victim to the unending human sex drive
Claws are curved and and difficult to craft things outside stone tools with, humans would be the premier artisans, smiths, and artists by having our wonderful hands.
Humans would do worse in skirmishes, yes, where the brutish size and short engagement length of such engagements would favor the anthros. But a dog must pant, and a human may sweat, the longer the engagement is the better off humans are due to much better stamina and muscle adaptations.
The next is food, where humans are at an initial disadvantage, a lone farmer stands no chance against a group of wolf braves, but a town with bow and spear? definitely a challenge, a city with gendarme and militia? Unconquerable.
Another thing is social adaptations, the Anon last thread mentioned innate human xenophobia, something that only manifests if the culture is too different or no benefit is seen. Take the Berbers of the "Portuguese of Appalachia" where groups mixed and former new ones. Humans are xenophillic when there is something to gain or times are hard enough, a permanent siege would do just that. Any woman at the gates accepted with open arms, any tribe allied repelled from their homes given a place to tend their cattle. Not to mention an extremely high cap on group size.
So while humans would be physically weaker than most, or all anthros in one aspect or another, we humans have our strengths, and beyond adaptions. Shipbuilding is unique to humans, and fireants, so we'd exist, even if just as a merchant class.
